Intro to Mapping with GGPLOT and Rstudio

John Dreyfous

1/31/2023

In this tutorial, I will create a map visualizing the 2021 Annual Global GDP by Country using ggplot. Maps are a powerful way of visualizing and interpretting data. With a personal interst in GIS, this method of mapping seemed like an intersting alternive to learn in place of qGIS or ARC.

Step One: Install Packages and Download Data

#install.packages("ggplot2")   #only do this once
#install.packages("tidyverse") #only do this once

To check if you have already installed these packages: find.package(<package.name>)

library(ggplot2) # Load library with each session
library(tidyverse) # Load library with each session

worldGDP<- read.csv("GlobalGDP3.csv")
mapData<-map_data("world")



#View(mapData) 
#View(worldGDP)

This GDP data was acquired from The World Bank. The World Bank has a large variety of easily accseible .csv data sets, which can be uplaoded and used in Rstudio.

map_data(world): data set that provides (Longitude, Latitude) for the borders of every country of the world. This data set also includes sub regions, such as the states in the USA.

In Excel, I removed unnecessary columns before uploading to Rstudio, so the uploaded .csv contained only Country Name and GDP ## Step Two: Clean Your Data

colnames(worldGDP)[1] ="region" 

mapData<-left_join(mapData, worldGDP, by = "region") # Function works simiarly to group_by and joins GDP into mapData by region (ie. country name)

Column names in mapData and worldGDP must match EXACTLY in order for information to be grouped together correctly. Rows names must also match EXACTLY. If GDP information data does not populate a country when mapped, double check that the column: region names are the same.

Step Three: Make and Customize Your Map

map1<-ggplot(mapData, mapping=aes(x= long, y=lat, group=group)) + geom_polygon(aes(fill= GDP), color="black")

map1 creates a basic map visualizing the 2021 Annual GDP by country. It uses a default color gradient and fills the borders of countries with color=black

# install.packages("viridis") 
# install.packages("RColorBrewer") # only have to do this once
library(viridis)
## Loading required package: viridisLite
library(RColorBrewer)

viridis and RColorBrewer are packages of pallets to help visualzie data. Viridis contains a handful of gradient color pallets, while RColorBrewer is the pre-installed set of color palettes for use in data visualization.

Feel free to experiment with the color spectrum that best suits your data set

map2 <- map1 + scale_fill_viridis(name="Annual GDP (billions)", option="plasma")+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(), # removes X-axis text
        axis.text.y = element_blank(), # removes y-axis text
        axis.ticks = element_blank(), # removes x-axis grid line
        axis.title.y=element_blank(), # removes y-axis title
        axis.title.x=element_blank(), # removes x-axis title
        rect = element_blank())
map2

Once you have loaded your library with the necessary color palettes, scale_fill_viridis() allows you to select a color spectrum.

To view all available schemes in RColorBrewer: display.brewer.all()

Color Blind Friendly: display.brewer.all(colorblindFriendly=TRUE)

Sequential Gradients: display.brewer.all(type="seq")

If you have made it this far, you have successfully replicated a map using ggplot.

This is one of many tools available to map in Rstudio. To use Google Maps generated maps, you can use ggmaps(). Alternatively, maps can be downloaded for use in Rstudio from OpenStreetMap.
